1549135659007.attack: The attackers can manipulate some files present in the kernel to cause a denial of service attack. There are other functions present in the kernel that have a few bugs, and the majority of these lead to DoS attacks. Most of the high-level threats present in the CVE database pertaining to this specific linux kernel lead to DoS attacks and given that the device is a gateway/router for other users, a DoS attack can cause serious trouble for people connected.
1549135659007.efforts:
We first believed that the kernel was easily exploitable because of easy to guess user details for the router. In this device's case, the password was set to the default one given to the device before it got shipped. This password is easy to crack and most routers have their default passwords encoded in their Mac Address. Therefore, it made sense for the device's kernel to be vulnerable to attacks since the outer layer of security was non-existent. 
We tried changing the password to a more secure one, but it didn't work. We're unsure of how to fix these bugs in the kernel code itself, and the device also does not have any option to upgrade its firmware either.
1549135659007.references:
We used the CVE database to find the exploitability of the vulnerability, using this link:
https://www.cvedetails.com/vulnerability-list/vendor_id-33/product_id-47/version_id-194310/opdos-1/Linux-Linux-Kernel-3.10.53.html

1550408169022.attack: The POSIX subsystem implementation is prone to a local buffer overflow vulnerability. A local attacker may exploit this vulnerability in order to run code with elevated privileges, fully compromising the vulnerable system. It also allows remote attackers to cause a denial of service or possibly have unspecified other impact according to the tenda router vulnerabilities in the CVE database.
1550408169022.efforts: To patch the given vulnerability, it is required to disable POSIX on your router's OS. We tried to access the router's OS to disable POSIX and even tried contacting the network administrator but according to administrators, we unfortunately don't have access to do so.

1549299850844.attack:
* The usbvision driver in the Linux kernel package 3.10.0-123.20.1.el7 through 3.10.0-229.14.1.el7 in Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) 7.1 allows physically proximate attackers to cause a denial of service (panic) via a nonzero bInterfaceNumber value in a USB device descriptor [1]. 
* Red Hat Enterprise Linux is prone to a local denial-of-service vulnerability. 
* Attackers can exploit this issue to cause the kernel to crash, denying service to legitimate users.

1549353590921.attack: The attacker can do the overflow and DoS attacks on the outdated linux kernel version.
1549353590921.efforts: We tried to update the firmware, first by custom which was not available, then we contacted Huawei(owners of the router) and Optix(my ISP) who upgraded the firmware of the router. Sadly the updated firmware still had the outdated linux kernel version. Although getting administrative access to router gave me to checkbox the router to prevent several types of DoS attacks, it still was not enough to pass the ferret test.
1549353590921.references:
1. The help site of huawei: https://support.huawei.com/enterprise/en/access-network/echolife-hg8247h-pid-8952137/knowledge-base
2. Optix costumer support

1549550519466.attack: Owing to the vulnerabilities, an attacker could potentially perform various attacks ranging from rendering the system useless, gaining root access to the whole operating system, gaining all of the confidential data or execution of malicious code remotely.
1549550519466.efforts: First, we checked the version of the vulnerable Linux kernel. Next, we searched the CVE database of the vulnerabilities associated with that kernel version. We selected a few vulnerabilities that were threatening and could easily be patched. For example, one of the vulnerability we tried to solve is https://www.cvedetails.com/cve/CVE-2017-17053/. At the end of the page, there is a probable fix for this vulnerability. But unfortunately, our router's firmware is in binary format, and there is no way to access the source code of the firmware. As a consequence, we are unable to actually fix the vulnerabilities in our router.

1549355938005.attack: The Linux kernel before 4.1x.x mishandles certain privacy issues in yurex_read in drivers/usb/misc/yurex.c. Local attackers could use user access read/writes with incorrect bounds checking in the yurex USB driver to crash the kernel or potentially escalate privileges.
1549355938005.efforts: We were not able to patch the device because we can not update the software or upgrade the firmware of our Huawei router ourselves. There is a DoS configuration, however, we can not change it manually. Moreover, in our router settings there was no option for firmware update. Therefore, our device could not be patched.
1549355938005.references:
The resource that also verified that there is no software update available:
https://support.huawei.com/enterprise/en/access-network/echolife-hg8247h-pid-8952137/software
Resource with a list of potential vulnerabilities:
https://www.cvedetails.com/vulnerability-list/vendor_id-33/product_id-47/version_id-125926/Linux-Linux-Kernel-2.6.34.10.html

1549105090282.attack:
Vulnerability mentioned for our device was too broad, we did some research and here are the two vulnerability that we feel are closest:
1.	A local attacker can bypass security restrictions on a targeted system due to vulnerability in POSIX signal processing in Linux kernel
2.	A local attacker can cause denial of service condition on a targeted system due to a vulnerability in POSIX timer code of Linux kernel
1549105090282.efforts:
We tried searching for patches for the device but couldn’t found specific patches. Since POSIX is a broad term itself and we do not know what exactly the device is vulnerable of, so we were unable to patch the device. 
We tried understanding the two possible vulnerability available on cisco security bulletin.

1548699263515.attack:
Linux kernels up to and including version 4.13.1 had numerous vulnerabilities, such as:
1. Integer underflow in the l2cap_config_req function in net/bluetooth/l2cap_core.c in this Linux kernel allows remote attackers to cause a denial of service (heap memory corruption) 
2. The native Bluetooth stack in the Linux Kernel (BlueZ) is vulnerable to a stack overflow vulnerability in the processing of L2CAP configuration responses resulting in Remote code execution in kernel space.
1548699263515.efforts: I will have to purchase a router with an updated Linux version, and I will do that as soon as possible. I cannot fix the code by delving in the Linux kernel of my router as that will be nearly impossible.

1549785228221.efforts: We tried updating the firmware using the manufacturer's website. After the update ferret v0.7 didn't show any vulnerabilities (although the ferret app didn't show any vulnerabilities before either, only the ferret website did, so we can be sure. And the ferret app took too long to generate the new key so we couldn't verify).

1549044069996.attack: An issue was discovered in the Linux kernel through 4.17.3. An Integer Overflow in kernel/time/posix-timers.c in the POSIX timer code is caused by the way the overrun accounting works. Depending on interval and expiry time values, the overrun can be larger than INT_MAX, but the accounting is int based. This basically makes the accounting values, which are visible to user space via timer_getoverrun(2) and siginfo::si_overrun, random. For example, a local user can cause a denial of service (signed integer overflow) via crafted mmap, futex, timer_create, and timer_settime system calls.
1549044069996.efforts: Administrators are advised to contact the vendor regarding future updates and releases. we will send an email to the vendor to discuss that posix has this vulnerability and can be exploited causing denial of service attack.

1549172081953.attack:
1.  Local attackers could use user access read/writes with incorrect bounds checking in the yurex USB driver to crash the kernel or potentially escalate privileges.
2. Integer underflow in the l2cap_config_req function in net/bluetooth/l2cap_core.c in the Linux kernel before 3.0 allows remote attackers to cause a denial of service
3. net/dns_resolver/dns_key.c in the Linux kernel before 2.6.38 allows remote DNS servers to cause a denial of service
1549172081953.efforts:
I tried updating the router software through the admin login page, but it wasn't able to do so.

Integer underflow may be avoided by using a library that, after performing arithmetic, checks the value in question before returning it.

When a DNS resolver key is instantiated with an error indication, attempts to
read that key will result in an oops because user_read() is expecting there to be a payload - and there isn't one.
Give the DNS resolver key its own read handler that returns the error cached in key->type_data.x[0] as an error rather than crashing.
Also make the kenter() at the beginning of dns_resolver_instantiate() limit the
amount of data it prints, since the data is not necessarily NULL-terminated
